    "educational_notes": {
      "verse_context": "This verse, along with the one that follows it ('And whoever does an atom's weight of evil will see it.'), concludes Surah Az-Zalzalah. The surah vividly describes the cataclysmic earthquake that will signal the Day of Judgment, when the Earth will give up its burdens and testify to all that was done upon it. These final verses serve as the ultimate summary of accountability.",
      "theme_explanation": "The theme is the meticulous and inescapable justice of Allah. The phrase 'mithqala dharrah' (an atom's weight) emphasizes that nothing is too small to be recorded and judged. It serves as both a profound encouragement to do good, no matter how insignificant it may seem, and a stark warning against evil, no matter how trivial. It instills a deep sense of mindfulness (muraqabah) in a believer.",
      "surah_overview": "Surah Az-Zalzalah (The Earthquake) is a powerful, early Meccan surah. Its eight verses paint a dramatic picture of the Day of Resurrection. It describes the earth shaking violently, expelling its dead, and bearing witness to humanity's deeds. The surah's core message is the certainty of judgment and the perfect, detailed record of every action, culminating in the final two verses that establish the principle of absolute accountability."
